South African Stocks Decline for First Day in Three, led by Anglo Platinum

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a   a n d   R o b e r t   B r a n d
-- 
2011-04-15T15:36:10Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-15/south-african-equity-market-bhp-billiton-plc-nu-world-holdings.html
The FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index
snapped two days of gains, falling 190.67, or 0.6 percent, to
32,227.66 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg, taking the week’s
loss to 1.8 percent.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s largest mining
company, declined for the first day in three, falling 2.30 rand,
or 0.8 percent, to 280.10 rand. Copper fell for a fifth day on
the London Metal Exchange on concern record production in  China 
bolstered supplies and further government curbs on lending may
dim the outlook for domestic metal demand.  Anglo American Plc (AAL)  , the diversified miner that
makes up 11 percent of the index, dropped 3.49 rand, or 1
percent, to 349 rand.  Nu-World Holdings Ltd. (NWL)  , a manufacturer of
household electrical goods, fell to the lowest since September
2010, declining 2.40 rand, or 10 percent, to 21.60 rand. The
white-goods maker said it expects earnings to drop by as much as
10 percent in the first half through February because of
“adverse trading conditions during the post-December trading
period in our local manufacturing and importing operations,”
according to a trading update released to the stock exchange.  Sekunjalo Investments Ltd. (SKJ)  , an  investment company ,
dropped to the lowest level in more than three weeks, falling 1
cent, or 2.5 percent, to 39 cents. The company expects earnings
per share to climb to as much as 1.54 cents in the first half
through February, Sekunjalo in a trading update to investors. A
year earlier the company earned 0.71 cents a share.  To contact the reporter on this story:
